I have the one from the car sitting right here now.

Yes, there are two motors. I can see the logo on one, &quot;SYNCHRON,&quot; and
the other is probably the same. One motor gets one white wire and the
red wire, and the other motor get the other white wire and the black
wire. There's a stamp on the framework that holds the motors that says
&quot;GRC-120VAC.&quot; Oh, you can set the hands by hand. There's a gear you
can reach with your fingertip. Above it are the instructions, &quot;to set
hands, turn gear in this direction,&quot; with an arrow pointing in one
direction. You can advance the hands, but you cannot turn them in
reverse. They move quickly; a small motion with the fingertip sends
them forward an hour.

The clock was tested in November 1968. It was made by the Standard
Electric Time Corp., 89 Logan Street, Springfield, Massachusetts. No
ZIP code for some reason. What do you want to bet that the replacement
clock is made in China?

They used to build Rolls-Royces in Springfield, didn't they?

These clocks look as if they'd be right at home in faked footage of an
alien autopsy. Either that, or you can relive the elementary school
hell of counting down the minutes waiting for three o'clock to roll
around. Finally.

Thanks.
