The red wire should be the motor to sync it to the master clock.  At
least, that was the color the sync wiring in the school buildings. The
clocks were synced by speeding the clock up, if it was out of sync.  I
think this was done at midnight, but I do know it was done when the
buildings were generally empty.

I worked for a TV shop 35 years ago, where the owner was an
independent Standard Electric Time servicer. I saw hundreds of those
clocks go through the shop that needed a complete rebuild. He had a
small master clock on one bench to test them with, after he completed
the repairs.

The biggest failure on these clocks was the motors.  He used to buy
them by the hundred, until they hit $90 each.

