They were a series that ran in &quot;Popular Electronics&quot; from 1954 to 1964.
It was fiction, and while they had real adventures, the real intent was
to convey some theory about something electronic (or peripheral topic)
Each was a standalone short story.  Carl &amp; Jerry started out has high
school students, and eventually went off to university, continuing
their adventures until someone got tired (I have no clue whether it
was the author's decision to stop writing them, or the magazine decided
to stop publishing them).

So they often were a good introduction to something electronic, and
sometimes they covered esoteric or new things.  So there was a story
about making a magnetometer and finding what turned out to be useless
junk on an old farm.  There was a story about the pair getting trapped
in a car and using the ignition system to send spark signals in the hopes
of catching someone's attention (it worked).  Another one, they get locked
in a backroom by burglars holding up a gas station (or maybe that was the one
with the plot to kidnap or kill an official), and they use their knowledge
of what's inside a phone (I think it was hashed out at the beginning of
the story when they sat around discussing the topic) to dial out even
though they didn't have an actual phone.

They weren't deeply technical, but they often did present a good
introduction to a topic.  For the magazine readers, on some level they
provided content to the beginner who might not yet have the knowledge
to understand the construction articles.

Like I said, some of them have been availalbe for years online
at http://home.gwi.net/~jdebell/pe/cj/cnjindex.htm

So now I've taken the time to find the other source, and it's
Jeff Duntemann who has gotten the rights to the stories and is
reprinting them in book form:
http://www.copperwood.com/carlandjerry.htm
He has a bunch of blog entries about the stories here:
http://jeff-duntemann.livejournal.com/tag/carl+&amp;+jerry

The author of the stories, John T. Frye, later had a similar
series of fictional stories that conveyed some technical knowledge.
It was set in a tv repair shop, and was called something like
&quot;Mac's Repair Shop&quot;.

Michael
