I have a school clock made by Simplex. It uses a 110 VAC motor for the
main drive and a 110 VAC solenoid which rachets the hand a minute at a
time. This is the only way to set the clock other than waiting for the
time to be the same as what's currently on the clock and then plugging
it in.

When I attended school, The Portland Public School system used a similar
clock system. Whenever a reset was required, the hands would advance
about 10 or 15 minutes every minute and you could hear the ker-chunk of
the solenoid repeatedly. I suspect that this gradual process was
designed to avoid exceeding the duty cycle of the solenoid.

I don't think there was any way for the system to read what a particular
clock was set to. I suspect that they were all initially calibrated with
the same time and the assumption thereafter was that all of them would
display the same time.

