I wanted to hang the clock on my office wall, without any wires dangling
from it - this is 20 years ago. I used a perf board to build a little
battery-powered xtal oscillator, followed by a CMOS divider to get to
one pulse per minute. That pulse turned on a Darlington-pair transistor,
which pulsed the solenoid. It worked well, except that the pulse had to
be about 1 second long. Even at that low duty cycle, I needed some
pretty hefty dry cells to get a reasonable life out of the thing. The
divider chain was pretty power-hungry, too.

If you don't mind a line cord dangling from the clock, this approach
works well.

Bill
